{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17628929","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17628929"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:02:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:02:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17251"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17251","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17251"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.83,0.05,0.1,0,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9941"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69601"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9941","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9941"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17251"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55053"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4911"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"6878"},{"type":"tags","id":"7179"},{"type":"tags","id":"7184"},{"type":"tags","id":"9999"},{"type":"tags","id":"10293"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23304"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23323"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69601","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69601"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ESalivary glands produce approximately 1.5 litres of saliva per day. This secretion is tightly regulated by the autonomic nervous system.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary neural control of salivation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Parasympathetic stimulation via facial nerve","Somatic innervation via trigeminal nerve","Sympathetic stimulation via vagus nerve","Direct hormonal control via secretin","Sympathetic stimulation via superior cervical ganglion"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary control of salivation is through \u003Cstrong\u003Eparasympathetic stimulation via the facial nerve\u003C/strong\u003E. Parasympathetic nerve fibres release acetylcholine, which acts on muscarinic receptors to stimulate fluid and electrolyte secretion, producing copious watery saliva.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESympathetic stimulation via vagus nerve\u003C/strong\u003E - The vagus nerve does not innervate salivary glands, and sympathetic stimulation produces thick, protein-rich saliva in small volumes\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect hormonal control via secretin\u003C/strong\u003E - While secretin affects pancreatic secretion, it does not directly control salivation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESomatic innervation via trigeminal nerve\u003C/strong\u003E - Salivation is controlled by autonomic, not somatic, innervation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESympathetic stimulation via superior cervical ganglion\u003C/strong\u003E - While sympathetic nerves from the superior cervical ganglion do innervate salivary glands, they play a minor role in salivation\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EParasympathetic stimulation accounts for about 90% of salivary secretion. The sympathetic system plays a minor role, primarily affecting protein content rather than fluid volume.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Salivation is primarily controlled by parasympathetic innervation via the facial nerve (cranial nerve VII).","Acetylcholine acts on muscarinic receptors in salivary glands to increase fluid and electrolyte secretion.","Sympathetic stimulation produces protein-rich but low-volume saliva."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Boron W. F., Boulpaep E. L. Medical Physiology. (3rd edition). US. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2017."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55053"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17251"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55053","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55053"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-12T11:16:45+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-12T11:17:13+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9941"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69601"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"ite